[30;1m90 | [0m[35m        As with all cluster managers the VM resources, Docker image, etc are all configurable.[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m92 | [0m[35m        You can then connect a client and work with the cluster as if it were on your local machine.[0m

[30;1m30 | [0m[35mWhen a task in your computation fails, the standard way of understanding what[0m
[30;1m31 | [0m[35mwent wrong is to look at the exception and traceback.  Often people do this[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35mwith the ``pdb`` module, IPython ``%debug`` or ``%pdb`` magics, or by just[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35mlooking at the traceback and investigating where in their code the exception[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35moccurred.[0m

[30;1m232 | [0m[35mthe cache, and increase in memory usage. Immediately after this task ends, the[0m

[30;1m68 | [0m[35mDask provides a few tools for profiling execution. As with the ``ProgressBar``,[0m
[30;1m69 | [0m[35mthey each can be used as context managers or registered globally.[0m
[30;1m70 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m71 | [0m[35mThe ``Profiler`` class is used to profile Dask's execution at the task level.[0m
[30;1m72 | [0m[35mDuring execution, it records the following information for each task:[0m
[30;1m73 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m74 | [0m[35m1. Key[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m95[0m[34m of [0m[33m2316[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/dask-2025.3.0/docs/source/diagnostics-local.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m256 | [0m[35m3. ``pretask(key, dsk, state)``: Run every time a new task is started.[0m
[30;1m257 | [0m[35mReceives the key of the task to be run, the Dask graph, and the scheduler state[0m
[30;1m258 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m259 | [0m[35m4. ``posttask(key, result, dsk, state, id)``: Run every time a task is finished.[0m
[30;1m260 | [0m[35mReceives the key of the task that just completed, the result, the Dask graph,[0m
[30;1m261 | [0m[35mthe scheduler state, and the id of the worker that ran the task[0m
[30;1m262 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m96[0m[34m of [0m[33m2316[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/dask-2025.3.0/docs/source/diagnostics-local.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m253 | [0m[35m2. ``start_state(dsk, state)``: Run at the beginning of execution, right[0m
[30;1m254 | [0m[35mafter the state is initialized.  Receives the Dask graph and scheduler state[0m
[30;1m255 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m256 | [0m[35m3. ``pretask(key, dsk, state)``: Run every time a new task is started.[0m
[30;1m257 | [0m[35mReceives the key of the task to be run, the Dask graph, and the scheduler state[0m
[30;1m258 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m259 | [0m[35m4. ``posttask(key, result, dsk, state, id)``: Run every time a task is finished.[0m

   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m

[30;1m280 | [0m[35mAvoid repeatedly putting large inputs into delayed calls[0m
[30;1m281 | [0m[35m--------------------------------------------------------[0m
[30;1m282 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m283 | [0m[35mEvery time you pass a concrete result (anything that isn't delayed) Dask will[0m
[30;1m284 | [0m[35mhash it by default to give it a name.  This is fairly fast (around 500 MB/s)[0m
[30;1m285 | [0m[35mbut can be slow if you do it over and over again.  Instead, it is better to[0m
[30;1m286 | [0m[35mdelay your data as well.[0m

[30;1m129 | [0m[35mEvery ``dask.delayed`` function call is a single operation from Dask's perspective.[0m
[30;1m130 | [0m[35mYou achieve parallelism by having many delayed calls, not by using only a[0m
[30;1m131 | [0m[35msingle one: Dask will not look inside a function decorated with ``@dask.delayed``[0m
[30;1m132 | [0m[35mand parallelize that code internally.  To accomplish that, it needs your help to[0m
[30;1m133 | [0m[35mfind good places to break up a computation.[0m
[30;1m134 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m103 | [0m[35mWe used the ``dask.delayed`` function to wrap the function calls that we want[0m
[30;1m104 | [0m[35mto turn into tasks.  None of the ``inc``, ``double``, ``add``, or ``sum`` calls[0m
[30;1m105 | [0m[35mhave happened yet. Instead, the object ``total`` is a ``Delayed`` result that[0m
[30;1m106 | [0m[35mcontains a task graph of the entire computation.  Looking at the graph we see[0m
[30;1m107 | [0m[35mclear opportunities for parallel execution.  The :doc:`Dask schedulers <scheduling>`[0m
[30;1m108 | [0m[35mwill exploit this parallelism, generally improving performance (although not in this[0m
[30;1m109 | [0m[35mexample, because these functions are already very small and fast.)[0m

[30;1m124 | [0m[35mCache tasks, not expressions[0m
[30;1m125 | [0m[35m----------------------------[0m
[30;1m126 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m127 | [0m[35mThis caching happens at the low-level scheduling layer, not the high-level[0m
[30;1m128 | [0m[35mDask DataFrame or Dask Array layer.  We don't explicitly cache the column[0m
[30;1m129 | [0m[35m``df.amount``.  Instead, we cache the hundreds of small pieces of that column[0m
[30;1m130 | [0m[35mthat form the dask graph.  It could be that we end up caching only a fraction[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m355[0m[34m of [0m[33m2316[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m114 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m115 | [0m[35m.. code-block:: python[0m
[30;1m116 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m117 | [0m[35m   >>> df.amount.max().compute()  # slow the first time[0m
[30;1m118 | [0m[35m   1000[0m
[30;1m119 | [0m[35m   >>> df.amount.min().compute()  # fast because df.amount is in the cache[0m
[30;1m120 | [0m[35m   -1000[0m
[30;1m121 | [0m[35m   >>> df.id.nunique().compute()  # starts to push out df.amount from cache[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m356[0m[34m of [0m[33m2316[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m

   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m99 | [0m[35m   >>> cache = Cache(2e9)  # Leverage two gigabytes of memory[0m
[30;1m100 | [0m[35m   >>> cache.register()    # Turn cache on globally[0m
[30;1m101 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m102 | [0m[35mNow the cache will watch every small part of the computation and judge the[0m
[30;1m103 | [0m[35mvalue of that part based on the three characteristics listed above (expensive[0m
[30;1m104 | [0m[35mto compute, cheap to store, and frequently used).[0m
[30;1m105 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m357[0m[34m of [0m[33m2316[0m[31m ]--[0m

       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m

   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35mAutomatic Opportunistic Caching[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35m-------------------------------[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35mAnother approach is to watch *all* intermediate computations, and *guess* which[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35mones might be valuable to keep for the future.  Dask has an *opportunistic[0m
[30;1m85 | [0m[35mcaching mechanism* that stores intermediate tasks that show the following[0m
[30;1m86 | [0m[35mcharacteristics:[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m358[0m[34m of [0m[33m2316[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/dask-2025.3.0/docs/source/caching.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35mTwo Simple Solutions[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35m--------------------[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35mIf we know ahead of time that we want both the maximum and minimum, we can[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35mcompute them simultaneously.  Dask will share intermediates intelligently,[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35mreading through the dataset only once:[0m

[30;1m27 | [0m[35mour algorithm.  We want to choose a task that lets us free memory now and in[0m

[30;1m32 | [0m[35mthe task that was most recently made available, quite possibly by the worker[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35mthat just returned to us.  This encourages the general theme of finishing[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35mthings before starting new things.[0m

[30;1m298 | [0m[35m        will remember/cache the path to this reducer node.[0m

[30;1m18 | [0m[35mThe asynchronous scheduler maintains indexed data structures that show which[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35mtasks depend on which data, what data is available, and what data is waiting on[0m

[30;1m34 | [0m[35mFor performance, a good choice of ``chunks`` follows the following rules:[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35m1.  A chunk should be small enough to fit comfortably in memory.  We'll[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35m    have many chunks in memory at once[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35m2.  A chunk must be large enough so that computations on that chunk take[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35m    significantly longer than the 1ms overhead per task that Dask scheduling[0m
[30;1m40 | [0m[35m    incurs.  A task should take longer than 100ms[0m

[30;1m365 | [0m[35mfull array (can't have larger chunks than the array itself) and to find[0m

[30;1m368 | [0m[35mThese values can also be used when creating arrays with operations like[0m
[30;1m369 | [0m[35m``dask.array.ones`` or ``dask.array.from_array``[0m

[30;1m126 | [0m[35mChunks Examples[0m
[30;1m127 | [0m[35m---------------[0m
[30;1m128 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m129 | [0m[35mIn this example we show how different inputs for ``chunks=`` cut up the following array::[0m

[30;1m47 | [0m[35mby ``mean``; then recomputed and again immediately pipelined into the subtraction[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35mfollowed by reduction with ``max``. This results in a much smaller peak memory usage as[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35mthe full ``x`` array is no longer loaded into memory. However, the tradeoff is that the[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35mcompute time increases as ``x`` is computed twice.[0m
